WEBVTT

00:00:07.150 --> 00:00:07.560
PROFESSOR: Hi.

00:00:07.560 --> 00:00:09.140
Welcome back to recitation.

00:00:09.140 --> 00:00:10.970
Today we're going to
do another example

00:00:10.970 --> 00:00:12.210
of a definite integral.

00:00:12.210 --> 00:00:14.950
This time, it's going to be one
that you're going to need

00:00:14.950 --> 00:00:16.810
to do some substitution for.

00:00:16.810 --> 00:00:18.580
You're not going to know the
antiderivative right off the

00:00:18.580 --> 00:00:19.820
top of your head, I think.

00:00:19.820 --> 00:00:21.710
So, I've got it on the
board behind me.

00:00:21.710 --> 00:00:25.180
So it's compute the integral
from minus 2 to 2 of the

00:00:25.180 --> 00:00:28.685
function x squared cosine
of the quantity x

00:00:28.685 --> 00:00:30.570
cubed over 8 dx.

00:00:30.570 --> 00:00:34.300
So, this is a kind of
weird a integrand.

00:00:34.300 --> 00:00:38.090
I roughly, you know, very, very
rough graph of kind of

00:00:38.090 --> 00:00:38.740
what it looks like.

00:00:38.740 --> 00:00:41.600
So this is sort of the
area of this region.

00:00:41.600 --> 00:00:43.870
It's a positive function
over this interval.

00:00:43.870 --> 00:00:47.260
So it's the area of this
region that I'm

00:00:47.260 --> 00:00:48.700
asking you to compute.

00:00:48.700 --> 00:00:51.690
So, all right, so definite
integral.

00:00:51.690 --> 00:00:54.180
Why don't you pause the video,
take a couple minutes, work

00:00:54.180 --> 00:00:56.730
this out yourself, come back,
we can work it out together.

00:01:03.780 --> 00:01:04.890
All right, welcome back.

00:01:04.890 --> 00:01:08.900
So, from looking at this
integrand here, it seems to me

00:01:08.900 --> 00:01:12.490
that I don't know immediately
off the top of my head what

00:01:12.490 --> 00:01:13.620
its antiderivative is.

00:01:13.620 --> 00:01:17.920
So, I can't just sort of apply
the fundamental theorem of

00:01:17.920 --> 00:01:20.580
calculus directly without
a little bit of work.

00:01:20.580 --> 00:01:24.480
So there are two different
ways that I can go about

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:25.188
computing this then,
about computing

00:01:25.188 --> 00:01:26.250
this definite integral.

00:01:26.250 --> 00:01:29.140
One is, that I can forget for
the minute that it's a

00:01:29.140 --> 00:01:32.140
definite integral and compute
the antiderivative and then

00:01:32.140 --> 00:01:34.180
use the fundamental theorem
of calculus.

00:01:34.180 --> 00:01:37.110
So, let's try that way first and
then we'll do it a second

00:01:37.110 --> 00:01:37.930
way as well.

00:01:37.930 --> 00:01:56.620
So, method one is to compute
the antiderivative.

00:01:56.620 --> 00:02:01.600
So we compute the antiderivative
of x squared

00:02:01.600 --> 00:02:06.430
cosine of x cubed over 8 dx.

00:02:06.430 --> 00:02:08.320
So here, it's not a definite
integral anymore.

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:10.410
Now I'm just looking at
the antiderivative.

00:02:10.410 --> 00:02:16.100
And so, OK, so either by
intelligent guessing or that--

00:02:16.100 --> 00:02:18.960
I forget if that's what
Professor Jerison called it--

00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:21.580
or by just a substitution
method.

00:02:21.580 --> 00:02:26.350
So, a good thing to substitute
here, is we see inside this

00:02:26.350 --> 00:02:29.570
function we have this x cubed
part and then outside we have

00:02:29.570 --> 00:02:30.670
an x squared part.

00:02:30.670 --> 00:02:34.960
So x squared dx, that's
closely related to the

00:02:34.960 --> 00:02:37.120
differential of x cubed.

00:02:37.120 --> 00:02:40.940
So we might try the
substitution.

00:02:40.940 --> 00:02:43.200
We might try the substitution
u equals--

00:02:43.200 --> 00:02:45.850
well we can maybe get rid of all
of that at once-- so make

00:02:45.850 --> 00:02:48.970
u equals x cubed over 8.

00:02:48.970 --> 00:02:57.550
So in that case, du is equal
to 3/8 x squared dx.

00:02:57.550 --> 00:03:02.950
And so this integral is equal
to the integral of--

00:03:02.950 --> 00:03:06.130
well so, x squared
dx, we have that.

00:03:06.130 --> 00:03:08.730
So we need to multiply
and divide by 3/8.

00:03:08.730 --> 00:03:16.470
So this is, 8/3 cosine
of u du.

00:03:16.470 --> 00:03:19.230
All right, and so now,
OK, so the 8/3,

00:03:19.230 --> 00:03:20.090
that's just a constant.

00:03:20.090 --> 00:03:20.990
That pulls out in front.

00:03:20.990 --> 00:03:22.140
That's not hard.

00:03:22.140 --> 00:03:25.790
So then the antiderivative
of cosine u du, that's

00:03:25.790 --> 00:03:26.820
something we know.

00:03:26.820 --> 00:03:35.140
So this is 8/3 of minus sine--

00:03:35.140 --> 00:03:38.670
sorry not minus; I was doing the
derivative instead of the

00:03:38.670 --> 00:03:39.620
antiderivative.

00:03:39.620 --> 00:03:42.300
Just 8/3 sine u.

00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:42.780
OK.

00:03:42.780 --> 00:03:44.350
And good.

00:03:44.350 --> 00:03:47.010
So that's the anti plus the
constant, which we don't need

00:03:47.010 --> 00:03:48.450
because we're going to plug
this in the fundamental

00:03:48.450 --> 00:03:50.100
theorem of calculus
in a minute.

00:03:50.100 --> 00:03:51.640
So it's 8/3 sine u.

00:03:54.540 --> 00:03:55.290
And, OK, so, but that's
not good.

00:03:55.290 --> 00:03:56.700
I need it back in
terms of my x's.

00:03:56.700 --> 00:03:58.410
And so I have to back
substitute.

00:03:58.410 --> 00:04:08.930
So this is 8/3 sine
of x cubed over 8.

00:04:08.930 --> 00:04:11.860
All right, now I've got an
antiderivative of this

00:04:11.860 --> 00:04:12.560
expression.

00:04:12.560 --> 00:04:14.980
So now I can take this
antiderivative and apply

00:04:14.980 --> 00:04:17.270
fundamental theorem of
calculus, Right?

00:04:17.270 --> 00:04:26.877
So, the integral from minus 2 to
2 of x squared cosine of x

00:04:26.877 --> 00:04:31.730
cubed over 8 dx is equal to--

00:04:31.730 --> 00:04:34.050
well it's equal to this
antiderivative--

00:04:34.050 --> 00:04:46.890
8/3 sine x cubed over 8 taken
between x equals minus 2

00:04:46.890 --> 00:04:48.480
and x equals 2.

00:04:48.480 --> 00:05:01.810
So this is equal to 8/3 times
sine of 1 minus 8/3 times sine

00:05:01.810 --> 00:05:03.720
of minus 1.

00:05:03.720 --> 00:05:07.230
OK, and sine of minus x is
equal to minus sine x.

00:05:07.230 --> 00:05:14.460
So we could rewrite this as
16/3 times sine of 1.

00:05:14.460 --> 00:05:15.270
So that's the answer.

00:05:15.270 --> 00:05:17.490
That's the value of
this integral.

00:05:17.490 --> 00:05:20.910
And we did this first method
by first computing the

00:05:20.910 --> 00:05:23.360
antiderivative and then using
it with the fundamental

00:05:23.360 --> 00:05:24.530
theorem of calculus.

00:05:24.530 --> 00:05:27.360
The second way we can do it is
the one that we just learned

00:05:27.360 --> 00:05:28.570
more recently in lecture.

00:05:28.570 --> 00:05:30.680
Which is to use substitution
directly in

00:05:30.680 --> 00:05:32.010
the definite integral.

00:05:32.010 --> 00:05:34.415
So let me come over
here and do that.

00:05:34.415 --> 00:05:35.665
So, method two.

00:05:55.210 --> 00:05:58.690
So now, when we do it
this way, mostly

00:05:58.690 --> 00:06:00.150
this looks the same.

00:06:00.150 --> 00:06:02.670
So we start off, we don't go
back to antiderivative.

00:06:02.670 --> 00:06:04.600
We start off with the
definite integral.

00:06:04.600 --> 00:06:05.850
So that's one difference.

00:06:10.350 --> 00:06:12.780
We can use the exact
same substitution.

00:06:12.780 --> 00:06:15.410
So we can use exactly the
substitution that we used

00:06:15.410 --> 00:06:17.740
before, which was u equals
x cubed over 8.

00:06:17.740 --> 00:06:18.990
That doesn't change.

00:06:24.300 --> 00:06:31.708
And we still have the same du is
equal to 3x squared over 8,

00:06:31.708 --> 00:06:35.345
but what does change--
sorry, dx.

00:06:35.345 --> 00:06:37.190
Good.

00:06:37.190 --> 00:06:42.830
You need a differential always
to be equal to a differential.

00:06:42.830 --> 00:06:46.600
So what does change
is that this--

00:06:46.600 --> 00:06:47.642
I need to change the bounds.

00:06:47.642 --> 00:06:48.290
Right?

00:06:48.290 --> 00:06:51.060
If I'm keeping it as definite
integrals all the time, so I'm

00:06:51.060 --> 00:06:55.210
changing here from an integral
with respect to x to an

00:06:55.210 --> 00:06:57.060
integral with respect to u.

00:06:57.060 --> 00:06:59.680
And so that means that when I
write down the second integral

00:06:59.680 --> 00:07:03.000
with respect to u, the bounds
that I write down have to be

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:04.410
the bounds for u.

00:07:04.410 --> 00:07:05.430
Not for x.

00:07:05.430 --> 00:07:09.060
So when x is equal to minus
2, I need to know what the

00:07:09.060 --> 00:07:11.220
corresponding value of u is.

00:07:11.220 --> 00:07:14.150
So in this case, when x is equal
to minus 2, we see that

00:07:14.150 --> 00:07:15.820
the lower bound here--

00:07:15.820 --> 00:07:17.520
when x is equal to minus 2--

00:07:17.520 --> 00:07:22.460
the lower bound on u becomes
u equals, well, minus

00:07:22.460 --> 00:07:24.220
2 cubed over 8.

00:07:24.220 --> 00:07:25.650
That's minus 1.

00:07:25.650 --> 00:07:29.890
And when x is equal to 2, the
upper bound, u becomes

00:07:29.890 --> 00:07:31.030
2 cubed over 8.

00:07:31.030 --> 00:07:32.170
So u becomes 1.

00:07:32.170 --> 00:07:34.700
So we have this extra step when
we do it this way, of

00:07:34.700 --> 00:07:36.990
changing the bounds.

00:07:36.990 --> 00:07:38.310
OK, so I do that.

00:07:38.310 --> 00:07:39.850
So now I get the integral.

00:07:39.850 --> 00:07:42.570
So I'm going to write u equals
minus 1 here just to remind

00:07:42.570 --> 00:07:47.070
myself that I made
this change to 1.

00:07:47.070 --> 00:07:50.000
OK, and now the inside
transforms exactly the same.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:58.340
So it's 8/3 times cosine u du.

00:07:58.340 --> 00:08:01.650
OK, and now again, this is
something for which I already

00:08:01.650 --> 00:08:02.910
know the antiderivative.

00:08:02.910 --> 00:08:05.880
So I apply the fundamental
theorem of calculus here.

00:08:05.880 --> 00:08:14.950
So I get the integral is equal
to 8/3 sine of u, where u goes

00:08:14.950 --> 00:08:17.210
between minus 1 and 1.

00:08:17.210 --> 00:08:20.120
So the other thing that's
changed here is that now I

00:08:20.120 --> 00:08:22.800
don't have to change this
back in terms of x's.

00:08:22.800 --> 00:08:26.050
I have the values that I'm going
to plug in here already

00:08:26.050 --> 00:08:27.250
in terms of u.

00:08:27.250 --> 00:08:29.410
So I don't have to switch
back in terms of x's.

00:08:29.410 --> 00:08:31.180
And so I just plug these
values in and take the

00:08:31.180 --> 00:08:31.870
difference.

00:08:31.870 --> 00:08:42.350
So this is equal to 8/3 sine of
1 minus 8/3 sine of minus

00:08:42.350 --> 00:08:49.150
1, which as we said before
is 16/3 times sine of 1.

00:08:49.150 --> 00:08:50.910
OK, so we have these two
different methods.

00:08:50.910 --> 00:08:53.980
They're very, very, very,
similar in how you apply them.

00:08:53.980 --> 00:08:57.200
The key differences are, that
when you do it, the

00:08:57.200 --> 00:08:59.550
substitution in terms of
definite integrals, you have

00:08:59.550 --> 00:09:01.400
to change your bounds
of integration.

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:04.680
And what you get for changing
your bounds of integration is

00:09:04.680 --> 00:09:08.960
at the end you don't have to
switch back from u's into x's.

00:09:08.960 --> 00:09:12.820
Whereas, if you do it by first
computing the antiderivative,

00:09:12.820 --> 00:09:15.630
well, you don't have any bounds
of integration when you

00:09:15.630 --> 00:09:18.090
compute the antiderivative so
you don't have to change them.

00:09:18.090 --> 00:09:20.770
But once you computed the
antiderivative, then you have

00:09:20.770 --> 00:09:23.490
to go and make your
back substitution.

00:09:23.490 --> 00:09:26.750
Put everything back in terms
of x's before going on to

00:09:26.750 --> 00:09:29.450
compute the definite integral
that you started with.

00:09:29.450 --> 00:09:32.750
So the those are the two
different ways you can do

00:09:32.750 --> 00:09:36.070
substitution in definite
integrals and

00:09:36.070 --> 00:09:38.050
I'll end with that.